        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Farnborough Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Jan<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> 23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Forbes</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>The Balanus from Bembridge, Barton &amp; Headon beds is the same species <hi rend="underline">B</hi>. unguiformis of Sowerby.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> The Headon specimens, about which I doubted are the best characterised &amp; are so perfect, as to be worth preserving. The specimens shall be taken care of, &amp; returned to you hereafter with others that I have of yours.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Most truly your’s | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD described these fossil specimens from Eocene formations of the southern British coast and the Isle of Wight in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4838.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Living Cirripedia</hi> (1854): </ref>296–8. He included short descriptions of the fossil forms of Balanidae and Verrrucidae in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4838.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Living Cirripedia</hi> (1854)</ref> because at this stage he was unsure that the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3646.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Palaeontographical Society</ref> would publish a work on the fossil species of these groups.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Forbes was among those thanked in the preface of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2622.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Fossil Cirripedia</hi> (1854)</ref> for having provided specimens.</note>
        </div>        
            
